    "id": "9092313e5fe625d9",
    "verdict": "dismissed",
    "confidence": 0.9,
    "triage_reasoning": "Reality — the literals 'openai' and 'openrouter' do appear in both files, but the framing misidentifies the contract type. These are **ecosystem provider names** defined externally by OpenAI and OpenRouter respectively. They appear throughout the entire codebase — in README.md, .env.example, .osoji.local.toml.example, pyproject.toml, all test files, and source modules.\n\nIn `test_llm_provider.py`, the tests at lines 63, 67, 75, and 85-87 are checking the observable API of `registry.py` (that it registers providers under these names). This is the standard producer/consumer pattern for unit tests — the test pins behavior the registry explicitly defines.\n\nSignificance fails — there is no silent mismatch path. If `registry.py` ever renamed its 'openai' key to something else, the `test_provider_names_include_all_supported_providers` assertion at line 63 would fail immediately and loudly. Extracting shared constants would not prevent any regression.\n\nThe strings are also partly ecosystem conventions — the providers are literally named OpenAI and OpenRouter.",
